Actually, I prefer DR-Dos.  While the help is somewhat laughable, and you
won't find out anything without a manual handy, it's still a decent, flexible
operating system.  Most of the public labs here at the University of Florida
were running DR-DOS 6.0 until recently;  (Yes, I know 6.0 is the old release,
but there was no reason to upgrade)  However, due to one minor *ahem* little
package, we were forced to upgrade to MS-DOS 6.22.  I suppose it's part of 
their effort to unify DOS and Windows into one conglomerate kludge, but it 
turns out that M$-Office will not work-- er, that should be "is not tested
with"-- any DOS other than M$-DOS 6.xx, while running on a network.

It also took them over a month to finally admit this to us, and in the
meantime, at least a third of the people using M$-Office were unable to save
their work, due to "Disk may be write-protected" errors, even when saving
to the hard drive.  Even now, Dos/Windows can't deal with a simple disk error
without M$-Office crashing, and taking the user's file with it.

And one other minor complaint:  Why hasn't M$ clued into the fact that command
line editing using the F-keys is ugly, and a pain?  I was dumbfounded that you
STILL have to load an external TSR (doskey) in order to edit command lines! 
Added to that, the "type" command is still missing the 15 or so lines to pause
the display at the end of each page.  (To be fair OS/2 is also lacking in this
regard;  But at least the OS/2 CLI has decent editing abilities)

I sincerely hope that M$ does a better job with Win9x.  While I'm a definite
OS/2 advocate, there are some problems with Warp that only pressure from
competition will cure;  And thus far, I don't SEE any competition.

